questions.question: A particle of mass $m = 2\text{ kg}$ is projected from the origin in the vertical $xy$-plane. The initial velocity is $v_0 = \sqrt{2}\text{ m/s}$ at an angle of $45^\circ$ with the $x$-axis. Taking the acceleration due to gravity as $g = 10\text{ m/s}^2$, determine the magnitude and direction of the angular momentum of the particle with respect to the origin when it reaches its maximum height.

Three blocks $A$, $B$, and $C$ are lying on a smooth horizontal surface. $A$ and $B$ have equal masses $m$, while $C$ has mass $M$. Block $A$ is given an initial speed $v$ towards $B$ due to which it collides with $B$ perfectly inelastically. The combined mass then collides with $C$, also perfectly inelastically. If $\frac{3}{4}$th of the initial kinetic energy is lost in the whole process, what is the value of $M/m$?

A particle moves a displacement $\vec{d} = \hat{i} - 2\hat{j} - \hat{k}$ under the application of a force $\vec{F} = 2\hat{i} + \frac{1}{2}\hat{j} + \hat{k}$. What is the total work done on the particle?

Two particles are placed at the coordinates $(0, 0)\text{ cm}$ and $(x, 0)\text{ cm}$ having masses $m_1 = 20\text{ kg}$ and $m_2 = 60\text{ kg}$ respectively. The particle of $20\text{ kg}$ is moved along the same line through a distance of $12\text{ cm}$ towards the other particle. The distance through which the $60\text{ kg}$ particle must be moved to keep the position of the centre of mass of the system unchanged is:
questions.option_c: $6\text{ cm away from the } 20\text{ kg particle}$
questions.option_d: $4\text{ cm away from the } 20\text{ kg particle}$

questions.question: A particle undergoes rotational motion with an angular acceleration given by $\alpha = 6t^2 - 2t$, where $t$ is the time in seconds and $\alpha$ is in $\text{rad s}^{-2}$. At $t = 0$, the initial angular velocity is $10 \text{ rad s}^{-1}$ and the initial angular position is $4 \text{ rad}$. Calculate the angular position of the particle at $t = 2 \text{ s}$.

A mass of $5\text{ kg}$ in the shape of a solid cylinder is wrapped with an inextensible light string and placed on a rough inclined plane at an angle of $60^\circ$. The string is pulled parallel to the incline. If the magnitude of the frictional force acting between the cylinder and the plane is $10\text{ N}$ while the cylinder is sliding, calculate the coefficient of kinetic friction between the cylinder and the surface. (Take $g = 10\text{ m/s}^2$)

A uniformly tapering conical wire is made from a material of Young’s modulus $Y$ and has a normal, unextended length $L$. The radii, at the upper and lower ends of this conical wire, have values $R$ and $3R$, respectively. The upper end of the wire is fixed to a rigid support and a mass $M$ is suspended from its lower end. The equilibrium extended length, of this wire, would equal:

A $100\text{ g}$ of iron nail is hit by a $1.5\text{ kg}$ hammer striking at a velocity of $60\text{ ms}^{-1}$. What will be the rise in the temperature of the nail if one fourth of energy of the hammer goes into heating the nail? [Specific heat capacity of iron $= 0.42\text{ Jg}^{-1\circ}\text{C}^{-1}$]

A sample of $500\text{ g}$ of ice at $-10^\circ\text{C}$ (specific heat $= 0.5\text{ cal g}^{-1}{^\circ}\text{C}^{-1}$) is mixed with $2000\text{ g}$ of water at $50^\circ\text{C}$ in a calorimeter. If the final state of the mixture consists entirely of water at $0^\circ\text{C}$, what is the calculated value of the latent heat of fusion of ice in $\text{cal g}^{-1}$?
A particle is executing simple harmonic motion with a time period $T$. At time $t = 0$, it is at its position of equilibrium. The kinetic energy–time graph of the particle will look like:

A water droplet of mass $0.1\text{ g}$ is suspended in equilibrium, prevented from falling by a vertical electric field of magnitude $9.8 \times 10^{5}\text{ N/C}$. Given $g = 9.8\text{ m/s}^2$, determine the value of the charge on the droplet in nanoCoulombs (nC).
A network of four capacitors of capacity equal to $C_1 = C$, $C_2 = 2C$, $C_3 = 3C$ and $C_4 = 4C$ are connected to a battery as shown in the figure. The ratio of the charges on $C_2$ and $C_4$ is:

A bar magnet of length $14\text{ cm}$ is placed in the magnetic meridian with its north pole pointing towards the geographic north pole. A neutral point is obtained at a distance of $18\text{ cm}$ from the center of the magnet. If $B_H = 0.4\text{ G}$, the magnetic moment of the magnet is: ($1\text{ G} = 10^{-4}\text{ T}$)
An electron moves on a straight line path $XY$ as shown. The $abcd$ is a coil adjacent to the path of electron. What will be the direction of current, if any, induced in the coil?
questions.option_a: The current will reverse its direction as the electron goes past the coil

questions.question: A square loop of wire with total length $L_{\text{total}}$, resistivity $\rho$, and a wire radius $r$ is placed in a uniform magnetic field oriented perpendicular to the plane of the loop. The magnetic field increases at a steady rate such that the change in field strength per unit time is $\frac{9}{25} \text{ T s}^{-1}$. Which of the following represents the correct algebraic expression for the current $I$ induced in the square loop?
Which of the following types of electromagnetic radiation possesses the smallest wavelength?

Two plane mirrors $A$ and $B$ are aligned parallel to each other as shown in the figure. A ray of light is incident at an angle $30^\circ$ at a point just inside one end of $A$. The plane of incidence coincides with the plane of the figure. The maximum number of times, the ray undergoes reflection (excluding the first one) before it emerges out is:
The following figure represents two biconvex lenses $L_1$ and $L_2$ having focal length $10\text{ cm}$ and $15\text{ cm}$ respectively. The distance between $L_1$ & $L_2$ is:

Consider a Young's double-slit arrangement where light of wavelength $400\text{ nm}$ produces an interference pattern on a screen. The angular position of the first minimum is measured to be $0.2^{\circ}$ when the experiment is conducted in air. Determine the new angular position of the first minimum if the entire experimental setup is submerged in a liquid with a refractive index of $4/3$.

Suppose a stationary electron of mass $m$ and charge $e$ is subjected to a uniform electric field of magnitude $2E$. Neglecting any relativistic corrections, find the time derivative of the electron's de-Broglie wavelength at any instant $t$.

A spherical point object is dropped from the summit of a $100\text{ m}$ high tower situated on a remote planet. If the local acceleration due to gravity is exactly $8\text{ m/s}^2$, calculate the total distance (in meters) the object travels during the final half-second ($0.5\text{ s}$) of its descent before reaching the surface.

Two systems undergoing simple harmonic motion are described by the displacement equations $y_1 = 10\sin \left( 3\pi t + \frac{\pi}{3} \right)$ and $y_2 = 5(\sin 3\pi t + \sqrt{3}\cos 3\pi t)$. Given that the amplitudes of these motions satisfy the relation $A_1 = \alpha A_2$, determine the value of $\sqrt{\alpha}$.

A solid sphere having a radius of $6\text{ m}$ is uniformly charged with a volume charge density of $2\text{ }\mu\text{C cm}^{-3}$. Given that the permittivity of free space is $\epsilon_0 = 8.85 \times 10^{-12}\text{ C}^2\text{ N}^{-1}\text{ m}^{-2}$, determine the total electric flux emerging from the sphere. Provide your answer in units of $10^3\text{ GN m}^2\text{ C}^{-1}$ as a rounded integer.

A capacitor with a capacitance of $10\text{ }\mu\text{F}$ is fully charged using a $220\text{ V}$ power supply. Following this, it is disconnected from the source and linked to an uncharged $5\text{ }\mu\text{F}$ capacitor, allowing the charge to redistribute across the two. If the resulting energy loss during this redistribution is given by the expression $\frac{X}{100}\text{ J}$, determine the value of $X$ to the nearest integer.

A massive stellar object is composed entirely of a substance $X$. It undergoes a fusion process where three nuclei of $X$ are converted into one nucleus of $Y$ ($3X \rightarrow Y + Q$). The total energy generation rate of this object is $5.808 \times 10^{30} \text{ W}$. Given that the atomic mass of $X$ is $4.0026 \text{ u}$ and the mass of $Y$ is exactly $12.0000 \text{ u}$, the rate of the fusion reactions (the number of $Y$ nuclei formed per second) is expressed as $n \times 10^{42} \text{ s}^{-1}$. Determine the value of $n$. [Take $1 \text{ u} = 931.5 \text{ MeV}$ and $1 \text{ eV} = 1.6 \times 10^{-19} \text{ J}$]

If the activation energies associated with these rate constants are $E_{a_1} = 60 \text{ kJ mol}^{-1}$, $E_{a_2} = 30 \text{ kJ mol}^{-1}$, and $E_{a_3} = 10 \text{ kJ mol}^{-1}$ respectively, calculate the net activation energy $E_a$ of the reaction in $\text{kJ mol}^{-1}$.
